00:39:42,484 --> 00:39:42,717
Bob...

719
00:39:42,718 --> 00:39:44,349
Who the hell are you?
What's your angle?

720
00:39:44,420 --> 00:39:47,821
Bob! We gotta be really
strategic about this. Methodical.

721
00:39:47,890 --> 00:39:50,620
And whatever you say
reflects on all of us.

722
00:39:50,693 --> 00:39:53,594
So we're gonna fight it, but
we're gonna do it the right way.

723
00:39:53,662 --> 00:39:55,459
How long is it gonna
take to get an answer?

724
00:39:55,531 --> 00:39:58,261
First, this is Ford.
It won't be quick.

725
00:39:59,301 --> 00:40:02,668
Second, patents.
Christ, they're a minefield.

726
00:40:02,738 --> 00:40:06,037
Not to mention, the patent
courts are totally jammed.

727
00:40:06,442 --> 00:40:08,000
It's gonna take
some time.

728
00:40:08,077 --> 00:40:12,309
Well, whatever it takes.
The point is, this is all gonna be okay.

729
00:40:14,516 --> 00:40:19,010
Good. And in the meantime, let's
go a little softer on the language.

730
00:40:22,925 --> 00:40:28,329
So, a lot of these formulas work
in opposition with one another.

731
00:40:28,397 --> 00:40:32,231
So that a capacitive
reactance,

732
00:40:33,535 --> 00:40:39,269
uh, varies inversely
with the product

733
00:40:40,676 --> 00:40:42,234
of both...

734
00:40:43,312 --> 00:40:44,745
Uh, frequency?

735
00:40:44,813 --> 00:40:46,713
Yeah. Did I
call on you?

736
00:40:47,549 --> 00:40:48,743
Sorry.

737
00:40:49,618 --> 00:40:53,486
Frequency, yes.
And capacitance. Make a note of it.

738
00:40:56,825 --> 00:40:58,725
I'm gonna take
a quick break.

739
00:41:00,596 --> 00:41:03,087
<i>Mr. Previck would appreciate
your patience in this matter.</i>

740
00:41:03,165 --> 00:41:07,499
Yes, well, I'd appreciate it if Mr.
Previck could return my phone call.

741
00:41:42,104 --> 00:41:44,732
Who is it?
- It's Mr. Kearns.

742
00:41:45,374 --> 00:41:46,636
Come in, Mr. Kearns.

743
00:41:46,709 --> 00:41:48,768
Oh, hi, Wade.
- Hi.

744
00:41:48,844 --> 00:41:50,334
Wade, did you
ask who it was?

745
00:41:50,412 --> 00:41:52,141
He did, Jean. Hi.

746
00:41:52,214 --> 00:41:54,444
Hi. Bob!
What's going on?

747
00:41:54,516 --> 00:41:56,507
Uh, is Gil here?

748
00:41:56,585 --> 00:41:59,554
It's not really a great time
right now. You should have called.

749
00:41:59,621 --> 00:42:02,522
Jean, hon, do you mind
getting me a refill?

750
00:42:02,591 --> 00:42:03,785
Sure, hon.

751
00:42:05,260 --> 00:42:06,727
Thanks, hon.
I'll just be a second.

752
00:42:06,795 --> 00:42:08,228
Okay.

753
00:42:10,065 --> 00:42:12,158
I'm sorry. I...
- Hang on a second.

754
00:42:12,234 --> 00:42:14,566
I thought we were gonna stay
in communication here, so...

755
00:42:14,636 --> 00:42:16,866
Don't you think it's a little outta
line, you coming over like this?

756
00:42:16,939 --> 00:42:19,931
Okay, well, you haven't
returned my calls in six days.

757
00:42:20,008 --> 00:42:21,566
I'm not sure
I like your tone.

758
00:42:21,643 --> 00:42:24,237
I'm through waiting. I'm not
gonna sit around and do nothing.

759
00:42:24,313 --> 00:42:25,803
You're not
doing nothing.

760
00:42:25,881 --> 00:42:28,543
You called the lawyer,
you pulled Taylor out of a mock trial.

761
00:42:28,617 --> 00:42:30,084
You're on everybody.

762
00:42:30,152 --> 00:42:32,552
You even called my father,
for crying out loud. He's sick!

763
00:42:32,621 --> 00:42:35,613
Tell me one thing.
Are you backing out of this?

764
00:42:36,525 --> 00:42:38,152
What I'm doing is
looking at our options

765
00:42:38,227 --> 00:42:40,661
like any sensible
person would.

766
00:42:40,729 --> 00:42:42,560
Of course they're stonewalling us.
What do you expect?

767
00:42:42,631 --> 00:42:44,656
So then we take
them to court!

768
00:42:44,733 --> 00:42:45,859
Is that right?

769
00:42:45,934 --> 00:42:50,200
This is Detroit, Bob.
I did $17 million in business last year.

770
00:42:51,006 --> 00:42:52,234
You want to guess what
I'm gonna do next year

771
00:42:52,307 --> 00:42:53,740
if I start taking my
customers to court?

772
00:42:53,809 --> 00:42:56,903
This is not about money. This is
about right and wrong, and you know it.

773
00:42:56,979 --> 00:42:58,446
For Christ's sake,
you're my friend!

774
00:42:58,514 --> 00:43:00,709
That's right. I am.

775
00:43:01,216 --> 00:43:03,275
Did you ask to be
involved in this deal?

776
00:43:03,352 --> 00:43:05,343
You need some
perspective.

777
00:43:05,788 --> 00:43:10,384
You need to take a hard look at reality
and realize what we're up against.

778
00:43:10,459 --> 00:43:11,892
It's not your
only good idea.

779
00:43:11,960 --> 00:43:15,726
You've been coming up with stuff
like this since you were 14.

780
00:43:18,200 --> 00:43:22,227
Now, I need to get back to my
dinner, so we'll continue this later.

781
00:43:23,572 --> 00:43:25,403
I'll go it alone.

782
00:43:25,474 --> 00:43:28,170
No. Leave it
alone. Bob?

783
00:43:29,978 --> 00:43:31,639
It's not over yet.

784
00:43:44,026 --> 00:43:46,017
I'm not gonna
back off of this.

785
00:43:46,528 --> 00:43:50,055
We don't have the money to
bring in lawyers right now,

786
00:43:50,132 --> 00:43:51,827
so we're gonna have to do the
legwork ourselves, and then...

787
00:43:51,900 --> 00:43:53,333
Are you talking about
suing Gil Previck?

788
00:43:53,402 --> 00:43:55,302
No. No, we're gonna go
after the Ford Motor Company.

789
00:43:55,370 --> 00:43:56,632
They're the ones that screwed us.
- What?

790
00:43:56,705 --> 00:43:58,104
Gil just let me down.

791
00:43:58,173 --> 00:43:59,265
Robert, slow down.
We're...

792
00:43:59,341 --> 00:44:01,070
No, no, we're gonna have
to dig up everything

793
00:44:01,143 --> 00:44:03,338
that's ever been
written about me. Okay?

794
00:44:03,412 --> 00:44:05,539
Character stuff,
everything.

795
00:44:05,614 --> 00:44:09,675
<i>This is my number one priority, Phyllis.</i>
<i>Whatever it's gonna take.</i>

796
00:44:10,619 --> 00:44:13,087
Josh, I'm gonna need at
least 10 new wiper motors.

797
00:44:13,155 --> 00:44:14,816
And some of the
earlier versions, too.

798
00:44:14,890 --> 00:44:16,289
Sure, Professor.
Not a problem.

799
00:44:16,358 --> 00:44:17,916
Good. And
circuit boards.

800
00:44:17,993 --> 00:44:19,984
Yeah, they just trash
the test models anyway.

801
00:44:20,062 --> 00:44:22,360
All right, um, where
are we gonna do this?

802
00:44:22,431 --> 00:44:25,628
I'll meet you at the first
lab on the second floor.

803
00:44:25,701 --> 00:44:26,861
Okay.

804
00:44:28,637 --> 00:44:30,229
Where's the
itemization file?

805
00:44:30,305 --> 00:44:32,773
All the files
are in here, hon.

806
00:44:32,841 --> 00:44:34,103
You should see a doctor.

807
00:44:34,176 --> 00:44:36,474
Oh, I'm fine.
Let's keep going.

808
00:44:36,545 --> 00:44:39,241
Previck Automotive
Legal Affairs.

809
00:44:39,314 --> 00:44:43,080
Something to bring their attention
that various automotive manufacturers

810
00:44:43,151 --> 00:44:46,552
are considering using
electronic intermittent wiper...

811
00:44:46,622 --> 00:44:47,646
I don't have it yet.

812
00:44:47,723 --> 00:44:50,556
Considering using electronic
intermittent wiper control...

813
00:44:50,626 --> 00:44:51,991
Do you want to list who?
- Yes.

814
00:44:52,060 --> 00:44:55,723
And that these are in direct
violation of patents jointly held

815
00:44:55,797 --> 00:44:58,766
by both Previck and
Kearns Corporation.

816
00:44:58,834 --> 00:45:01,826
As the inventor of the
Intermittent Wiper, I ask, no...

817
00:45:01,904 --> 00:45:04,304
I demand that they take
immediate legal action.

818
00:45:04,373 --> 00:45:07,240
"Demand" is too strong.
They're our friends.

819
00:45:07,309 --> 00:45:08,571
What difference
does it make?

820
00:45:08,644 --> 00:45:10,612
They're not gonna
read it anyway.

821
00:45:10,679 --> 00:45:11,668
Then why are
we doing this?

822
00:45:11,747 --> 00:45:13,214
Because it makes
me feel better.

823
00:45:13,282 --> 00:45:14,340
Does it?

824
00:45:14,917 --> 00:45:18,910
What is this file?
What is this?

825
00:45:21,456 --> 00:45:25,051
Kathy won it in the swim meet.
She wanted you to see it.

826
00:45:31,066 --> 00:45:33,933
This is a bad
case of psoriasis.

827
00:45:34,002 --> 00:45:36,937
Now, Phyllis, I want you to take
care of yourself. Use the medication.

828
00:45:37,005 --> 00:45:38,836
Here's the sample.
- Thanks.

829
00:45:38,907 --> 00:45:41,034
And I'm going to write
you a prescription.

830
00:45:41,109 --> 00:45:42,599
How long do I
take that for?

831
00:45:42,678 --> 00:45:44,509
Well, just a month.

832
00:45:45,647 --> 00:45:49,777
I don't know what's going on with you,
Phyllis, but this is all stress-related.

833
00:45:49,851 --> 00:45:52,684
You understand me? You have to
take the stress level way down.

834
00:45:52,754 --> 00:45:53,846
I'll be fine.

835
00:46:07,169 --> 00:46:08,727
Hello, Jean.
- Phyllis.

836
00:46:08,804 --> 00:46:10,635
How are the kids?
- Good.

837
00:46:12,841 --> 00:46:14,172
Phyllis.

838
00:46:16,178 --> 00:46:17,975
Why is Bob
doing this?

839
00:46:19,247 --> 00:46:21,078
He can't stand
being called a liar.

840
00:46:21,149 --> 00:46:23,549
Well, nobody's
saying that he is.

841
00:46:24,052 --> 00:46:25,383
They might as well be.

842
00:46:25,454 --> 00:46:29,254
Oh, for God's sake, Phyllis,
it's Ford. He can't win.

843
00:46:30,359 --> 00:46:31,986
Take care, Jean.

844
00:46:46,508 --> 00:46:48,339
Oh! God!

845
00:46:48,410 --> 00:46:51,311
Yeah.
Med school gives them to us.

846
00:46:51,380 --> 00:46:53,280
We use them
for crash tests.

847
00:46:53,348 --> 00:46:55,316
You should see it when we
drop them down elevator shafts.

848
00:46:55,384 --> 00:46:57,284
It's very instructive.

849
00:46:57,352 --> 00:47:00,412
I'll try that sometime.
Did you get the boards?

850
00:47:01,657 --> 00:47:02,885
What the hell is this?

851
00:47:02,958 --> 00:47:06,291
I know, it's just motors.
I couldn't get any circuit boards.

852
00:47:06,361 --> 00:47:07,419
Why not?

853
00:47:07,496 --> 00:47:11,091
They didn't have any extras. Didn't
have any complete units. I don't know.

854
00:47:11,166 --> 00:47:12,690
These are nothing.

855
00:47:12,768 --> 00:47:14,258
Hey, man, this is
the best I could do.

856
00:47:14,336 --> 00:47:15,997
This doesn't
help me, Josh!

857
00:47:16,071 --> 00:47:17,163
I'm sorry.

858
00:47:17,239 --> 00:47:19,469
What does that mean?

859
00:47:22,244 --> 00:47:23,768
Wait a minute.

860
00:47:25,147 --> 00:47:27,047
Did somebody
talk to you?

861
00:47:28,850 --> 00:47:31,512
Did you have a
conversation about me?

862
00:47:31,987 --> 00:47:33,079
What?

863
00:47:34,523 --> 00:47:36,491
Are you working
with them?

864
00:47:37,693 --> 00:47:39,126
Huh? You even know
who they are?

865
00:47:39,194 --> 00:47:40,718
Man, I gotta go.

866
00:47:40,796 --> 00:47:41,854
They're the...

867
00:47:41,930 --> 00:47:44,490
They're the ones who don't
give a shit about you!

868
00:49:33,642 --> 00:49:35,610
Hey! Hey!

869
00:49:37,279 --> 00:49:38,541
Come on!

870
00:49:39,581 --> 00:49:42,641
What the hell are you doing?
Hey! Hey!

871
00:51:39,901 --> 00:51:43,200
Look at this lady.
She had five babies at the same time.

872
00:51:44,806 --> 00:51:47,673
That's quintuplets,
that's what they're called.

873
00:51:54,082 --> 00:51:55,106
Hello.

874
00:51:55,183 --> 00:51:56,377
<i>Is this</i>
<i>Mrs. Robert Kearns?</i>

875
00:51:56,451 --> 00:51:57,475
Yes.

876
00:51:57,552 --> 00:52:00,112
<i>Mrs. Kearns, this is Trooper Dale with
the Maryland State Police Department.</i>

877
00:52:00,188 --> 00:52:00,412
Yes.

878
00:52:00,413 --> 00:52:02,816
<i>We've located your husband, ma'am.</i>

879
00:52:02,891 --> 00:52:03,983
Is he okay?

880
00:52:04,059 --> 00:52:05,651
<i>Well, he was found on a bus</i>
<i>outside of Brunswick.</i>

881
00:52:05,727 --> 00:52:09,185
A bus? Where is he?
May I speak to him, please?

882
00:52:09,264 --> 00:52:11,061
<i>Uh, no, ma'am,</i>
<i>he's not here.</i>

883
00:52:11,132 --> 00:52:13,532
<i>He's being transported</i>
<i>to a hospital facility in Rockville.</i>

884
00:52:13,601 --> 00:52:15,034
What happened?

885
00:52:15,103 --> 00:52:18,698
<i>Sorry, I don't know exactly, but you'll
hear from the hospital when he arrives.</i>

886
00:52:18,773 --> 00:52:19,762
<i>Will you be at</i>
<i>this number?</i>

887
00:52:19,841 --> 00:52:21,604
Yes, we'll be here.
Thank you so much.

888
00:52:21,676 --> 00:52:22,870
<i>Thank you, Mrs. Kearns.</i>

889
00:52:22,944 --> 00:52:24,434
Thank you.
<i>- Bye.</i>

890
00:52:43,631 --> 00:52:45,292
Hey, Bob.

891
00:52:49,738 --> 00:52:51,569
Chair or couch today?

892
00:52:51,639 --> 00:52:53,038
Your choice.

893
00:52:55,243 --> 00:52:57,006
How's it going?
- Okay,

894
00:52:57,612 --> 00:52:59,011
I guess.
- Good.

895
00:53:00,682 --> 00:53:03,708
I don't feel like I need
to talk about it today.

896
00:53:04,586 --> 00:53:05,678
Okay.

897
00:53:12,093 --> 00:53:14,186
It is hard getting past it.

898
00:53:14,496 --> 00:53:16,054
I'm sure it is.

899
00:53:21,036 --> 00:53:23,368
Did you write any
of these books?

900
00:53:23,905 --> 00:53:27,932
I did. There's a thesis and several
binders full of journal articles.

901
00:53:28,009 --> 00:53:33,208
How would you feel if another
doctor took credit for those?

902
00:53:33,948 --> 00:53:38,282
Just came along and
put his name on there.

903
00:53:38,720 --> 00:53:40,381
I take your point.

904
00:53:40,455 --> 00:53:44,050
But at the same time, if getting
my name back on those articles

905
00:53:44,125 --> 00:53:46,457
overwhelmed my responsibilities
here at the hospital,

906
00:53:46,528 --> 00:53:48,860
or kept me from
creating new work,

907
00:53:49,364 --> 00:53:51,932
would that be worth it?
Would it be healthy?

908
00:53:51,933 --> 00:53:52,731
I don't know.

909
00:53:52,801 --> 00:53:54,792
I can't answer that.

910
00:53:54,869 --> 00:53:57,360
Do you want to
continue fighting this?

911
00:53:57,439 --> 00:53:58,463
No.

912
00:54:01,176 --> 00:54:02,734
No. No, I don't.

913
00:54:24,032 --> 00:54:25,590
Thank you.
- Mmm-hmm.

914
00:54:35,610 --> 00:54:36,872
Who is that?

915
00:54:40,115 --> 00:54:41,912
Come on, you
guys. Tim?

916
00:54:55,363 --> 00:54:57,297
Come here, you. How you doing?
- Hi, Daddy.

917
00:54:57,365 --> 00:54:58,855
Hi, how are you guys?
- Daddy, I made you a picture

918
00:54:58,933 --> 00:55:00,161
Daddy!
- I'll get the bag.

919
00:55:00,235 --> 00:55:01,964
No, I got
the bag. Tim, let go!

920
00:55:02,036 --> 00:55:04,231
You look good.
- Where's Dennis?

921
00:55:04,339 --> 00:55:06,773
You okay? He's coming later.
He's just late.

922
00:55:06,841 --> 00:55:07,967
How are you, buddy?
- You okay?

923
00:55:41,809 --> 00:55:42,798
Hey.

924
00:55:47,715 --> 00:55:51,879
What do you say we round up the
board of directors and go for a ride?

925
00:55:55,223 --> 00:55:57,123
Kearns Corporation.
- Mmm.

926
00:55:59,427 --> 00:56:00,894
No, I'm fine.

927
00:56:23,785 --> 00:56:25,446
Let's see here.

928
00:56:27,322 --> 00:56:29,756
Mmm-hmm.
Mmm-hmm.

929
00:56:30,325 --> 00:56:33,385
How do you pronounce
your name? Kee-urns?

930
00:56:33,461 --> 00:56:34,450
Kearns.

931
00:56:34,529 --> 00:56:36,087
Mr. Kearns.

932
00:56:36,531 --> 00:56:39,159
An inventor.
Mmm-hmm.

933
00:56:39,467 --> 00:56:41,594
What have you invented?

934
00:56:41,736 --> 00:56:43,135
A lot of things.

935
00:56:43,204 --> 00:56:45,729
Yeah, my brother-in-law
does a lot of that.

936
00:56:45,807 --> 00:56:50,039
Never sold anything, though.
He's actually in pest control.

937
00:56:50,445 --> 00:56:52,640
You really a doctor?

938
00:56:52,714 --> 00:56:53,738
Ph.D.

939
00:56:53,815 --> 00:56:54,975
Uh-huh.

940
00:56:56,451 --> 00:56:59,852
Well, Doctor, take a look
at your information.

941
00:56:59,921 --> 00:57:02,719
Make sure it's correct.
Sign at the bottom.

942
00:57:04,692 --> 00:57:07,286
You'll probably get your
first check in about six weeks.

943
00:57:07,362 --> 00:57:09,660
Proceed to the third
window on your left.

944
00:57:09,731 --> 00:57:10,993
Thank you.

945
00:57:11,466 --> 00:57:12,763
Move forward.

946
00:57:27,515 --> 00:57:28,573
Hi.

947
00:57:31,719 --> 00:57:33,346
Can I talk to you
for a second?

948
00:57:33,421 --> 00:57:34,911
Am I in trouble?

949
00:57:35,223 --> 00:57:36,281
No.

950
00:57:48,002 --> 00:57:52,564
I know you're mad at me.
Is it because I embarrassed you?

951
00:57:54,676 --> 00:57:56,166
Because I got sick?

952
00:57:56,244 --> 00:57:57,677
I don't like
you like this.

953
00:57:57,745 --> 00:58:00,305
Okay. Well, that's why
I want to talk to you.

954
00:58:00,381 --> 00:58:03,282
I didn't like it like
it was before, either.

955
00:58:04,385 --> 00:58:06,478
I didn't do
anything wrong.

956
00:58:06,988 --> 00:58:10,856
Look, Dennis, if I don't fight
back, if I don't do something,

957
00:58:10,925 --> 00:58:13,325
I'm afraid I'm gonna start
feeling like I did before.

958
00:58:13,394 --> 00:58:15,294
And I can't
handle that.

959
00:58:17,665 --> 00:58:20,395
I got a lawyer.
And it's gonna be difficult.

960
00:58:20,468 --> 00:58:21,833
And it's gonna be
tough on your mom.

961
00:58:21,903 --> 00:58:25,202
And I may not be around as much.
And I need your help.

962
00:58:25,440 --> 00:58:29,399
You're just starting this all over again.
- No, this is different.

963
00:58:33,915 --> 00:58:36,042
Is that all you
have to say?

964
00:58:36,417 --> 00:58:37,475
Yeah.

965
00:58:46,227 --> 00:58:49,162
And I'll tell you something.
Now, I'm old-fashioned.

966
00:58:49,230 --> 00:58:53,564
I'm not out for the quick score.
This firm is in this for the long haul.

967
00:58:53,768 --> 00:58:56,999
That's why I'm very glad that
you're here today, Mrs. Kearns.

968
00:58:57,071 --> 00:58:59,938
From several phone calls with
Bob, I think I understand now

969
00:59:00,007 --> 00:59:01,269
what his level
of commitment is.

970
00:59:01,342 --> 00:59:03,742
But this is part
of your life, too.

971
00:59:04,345 --> 00:59:06,404
I'd like to know where
you stand on this.

972
00:59:06,481 --> 00:59:09,609
I want to understand
exactly what this would be.

973
00:59:09,717 --> 00:59:10,775
What it would
mean for us.

974
00:59:10,852 --> 00:59:11,910
Well, as long as
you know that

975
00:59:11,986 --> 00:59:15,683
suing one of the most powerful
corporations in the world is...

976
00:59:15,923 --> 00:59:19,484
It's not something you take on lightly.
I mean, let's be clear about this.

977
00:59:19,560 --> 00:59:21,084
Ford is just the first.

978
00:59:21,162 --> 00:59:23,960
We're gonna be bringing suits
against every automobile company

979
00:59:24,031 --> 00:59:26,158
that's infringed on your
husband's patents.

980
00:59:26,234 --> 00:59:27,929
But Ford's number one.

981
00:59:28,002 --> 00:59:31,665
Once they decided to put your
husband's invention on their car,

982
00:59:31,739 --> 00:59:35,231
they gave a green light to
every auto company in the world.

983
00:59:35,309 --> 00:59:37,504
"To hell with your husband,"
is what they said.

984
00:59:37,578 --> 00:59:41,412
Let me tell you something, Mrs. Kearns.
I believe in what I do.

985
00:59:41,983 --> 00:59:44,281
I believe in a little
thing called justice.

986
00:59:44,352 --> 00:59:47,219
These bastards think they can
walk all over anybody they want.

987
00:59:47,288 --> 00:59:51,156
But we're here to tell them that
they can't, that it stops right here.

988
00:59:51,225 --> 00:59:52,692
And I don't want you
to worry that this

989
00:59:52,760 --> 00:59:56,093
is gonna take over your time or
your life, because that's my job.

990
00:59:56,164 --> 00:59:58,792
All right? That's why
I went to law school.

991
00:59:58,866 --> 01:00:01,699
Ian, this is Dr. Bob Kearns
and his wife, Phyllis.

992
01:00:01,769 --> 01:00:03,134
This is Ian Meillor.
- How do you do?

993
01:00:03,204 --> 01:00:04,762
He's gonna be working
on this with me.

994
01:00:04,839 --> 01:00:06,864
I just want to
thank both of you

995
01:00:06,941 --> 01:00:08,875
for giving us the opportunity
to really make a difference here.

996
01:00:08,943 --> 01:00:11,503
One of the first items on our
agenda's gonna be discovery.

997
01:00:11,579 --> 01:00:13,911
Yeah, I cannot wait to see
what they've got in those files.

998
01:00:13,981 --> 01:00:17,314
We're gonna jump right into
it starting this afternoon.

999
01:00:18,085 --> 01:00:19,950
Thank you very much.

1000
01:00:20,755 --> 01:00:23,485
And one other thing, I'd like to
stay as involved in this as possible.

1001
01:00:23,558 --> 01:00:26,686
Of course. Of course, Dr. Kearns,
your help will be invaluable.

1002
01:00:26,761 --> 01:00:28,490
In fact, we have to
get... What is it?

1003
01:00:28,563 --> 01:00:29,168
Previck Auto.

1004
01:00:29,169 --> 01:00:31,123
Yeah. We have to
get them on board ASAP.

1005
01:00:31,199 --> 01:00:32,757
Think you can do
any good there?

1006
01:00:32,834 --> 01:00:33,926
I'll see.

1007
01:00:34,001 --> 01:00:35,025
Very good to meet you.
Thanks for coming in.

1008
01:00:35,102 --> 01:00:36,694
Thank you so much.
We're relieved. Thank you.

1009
01:00:36,771 --> 01:00:40,935
I mean, Jesus Christ,
Bob, it's just a windshield wiper.

1010
01:00:41,008 --> 01:00:46,844
To you, maybe. To that bartender up
there. But to me it's the Mona Lisa.

1011
01:00:46,914 --> 01:00:51,715
Well, you know what I mean. But I
just thought that when you got back,

1012
01:00:51,786 --> 01:00:53,879
you'd have a different perspective.

1013
01:00:53,955 --> 01:00:56,253
I do. I'm handling
it differently.

1014
01:00:56,858 --> 01:00:58,951
Maybe you are.
I don't know.

1015
01:01:01,629 --> 01:01:02,687
So what are
you gonna do?

1016
01:01:02,763 --> 01:01:07,200
I don't know. Maybe
I'm out of options.

1017
01:01:11,506 --> 01:01:13,303
Why don't you sue me?

1018
01:01:13,374 --> 01:01:17,310
<i>Kearns versus Previck.</i>
Got a nice sound to it.

1019
01:01:17,378 --> 01:01:19,346
Well, then
why wouldn't you?

1020
01:01:19,413 --> 01:01:22,143
You've sued everybody else.
What's wrong with me?

1021
01:01:22,216 --> 01:01:25,481
Nothing. Other than that
I've known you for 25 years.

1022
01:01:25,820 --> 01:01:28,220
Maybe you ought
to think about it.

1023
01:01:28,890 --> 01:01:31,882
Get your lawyer to draft a
letter threatening to sue us.

1024
01:01:31,959 --> 01:01:35,554
If we're lucky, we'll get a
quick settlement. You understand?

1025
01:01:38,733 --> 01:01:40,997
Then you can have
your damn patents.

1026
01:01:43,538 --> 01:01:44,664
Okay.

1027
01:01:44,739 --> 01:01:48,038
Okay, but, Bob, you gotta forget
my name when it comes to Ford.

1028
01:01:48,109 --> 01:01:51,306
We're not gonna testify against them.
We're not gonna appear.

1029
01:01:51,379 --> 01:01:53,540
I mean it.
Well, say it.

1030
01:01:54,248 --> 01:01:57,411
You won't testify.
Previck won't be involved in any way.

1031
01:02:00,388 --> 01:02:01,753
All right.

1032
01:02:01,822 --> 01:02:03,119
All right.

1033
01:02:05,326 --> 01:02:07,157
<i>Dear Dr. Kearns,</i>

1034
01:02:07,228 --> 01:02:09,389
<i>Previck Automotive has
received your demand letter</i>

1035
01:02:09,463 --> 01:02:12,296
<i>concerning the Kearns</i>
<i>Blinking Eye Wiper.</i>

1036
01:02:12,366 --> 01:02:15,733
<i>While Previck has acted in accordance
with the terms of our agreement,</i>

1037
01:02:15,803 --> 01:02:17,566
<i>in order to avoid litigation,</i>

1038
01:02:17,638 --> 01:02:22,268
<i>we have decided to assign to you our
rights to the registered patents.</i>

1039
01:02:22,343 --> 01:02:24,777
<i>You will now be the sole</i>
<i>owner of the patents.</i>

1040
01:02:24,845 --> 01:02:27,075
<i>Best regards, Gil Previck.</i>

1041
01:02:29,784 --> 01:02:31,911
No, you had back
there a nice bread

1042
01:02:31,986 --> 01:02:33,544
that's all twisted up with salt on it.
I don't know.

1043
01:02:33,621 --> 01:02:34,883
Yeah, we could
do that.

1044
01:02:34,956 --> 01:02:37,322
No, wait, there they are!
There they are. Phyllis, hi.

1045
01:02:37,391 --> 01:02:38,722
Hi. So good to see you.
- Hello, Bob.

1046
01:02:38,793 --> 01:02:41,762
Thank you, Jimmy. And would
you bring us a bottle of Mot?

1047
01:02:41,829 --> 01:02:42,853
Sure.

1048
01:02:42,930 --> 01:02:45,626
Sit down, sit down.
- Sounds like good news.

1049
01:02:45,700 --> 01:02:49,261
I'd say it is. In fact, you could
call this a celebration dinner.

1050
01:02:49,337 --> 01:02:51,032
This is exciting.

1051
01:02:51,839 --> 01:02:55,297
Would you like to know who
called me on the phone today?

1052
01:02:55,576 --> 01:02:57,043
Charlie Defao.

1053
01:02:57,712 --> 01:02:59,475
Well, you may not
know that name,

1054
01:02:59,547 --> 01:03:03,074
but he's the man Macklin Tyler
calls when it's closing time.

1055
01:03:03,818 --> 01:03:07,276
And he's not a man to waste
his time on trivial matters.

1056
01:03:07,989 --> 01:03:12,688
Bob, Phyllis,
I'm very pleased to report to you

1057
01:03:13,561 --> 01:03:17,053
that Ford has offered
to settle for $250,000.

1058
01:03:18,866 --> 01:03:22,029
Two hundred and fifty thousand dollars.
Oh, my gosh.

1059
01:03:22,103 --> 01:03:24,799
Settle? Now, what does that
mean in practical terms?

1060
01:03:24,872 --> 01:03:26,396
'Cause I thought we
weren't gonna pursue that.

1061
01:03:26,474 --> 01:03:28,203
No, that was
our agreement.

1062
01:03:28,275 --> 01:03:31,472
And we didn't do anything
to seek this settlement.

1063
01:03:31,946 --> 01:03:33,413
This is Ford's offer.

1064
01:03:34,649 --> 01:03:36,139
And, frankly, we're
a little surprised.

1065
01:03:36,217 --> 01:03:39,084
We're goddamned shocked,
excuse the language.

1066
01:03:39,153 --> 01:03:40,347
Happily shocked,
though.

1067
01:03:40,421 --> 01:03:44,983
Okay, but in this offer, do
they admit it was my invention?

1068
01:03:45,059 --> 01:03:46,651
That they lied about it.

1069
01:03:46,727 --> 01:03:48,285
In a settlement
like this,

1070
01:03:48,362 --> 01:03:51,331
it's customary that both sides
are enjoined from commenting.

1071
01:03:51,399 --> 01:03:53,924
What that means is, they don't
say it wasn't your invention.

1072
01:03:54,001 --> 01:03:57,095
No, absolutely not. No. No, no,
no, no. We wouldn't allow that.

1073
01:03:57,171 --> 01:03:58,798
But they won't say
they stole it.

1074
01:03:58,873 --> 01:04:01,740
No, but if they're
offering $250,000,

1075
01:04:01,809 --> 01:04:04,334
I think we can see
$350,000. Maybe four.

1076
01:04:04,412 --> 01:04:07,438
That's wonderful,
I think we'd like to think about it.

1077
01:04:07,515 --> 01:04:09,039
Sure, of course.

1078
01:04:09,116 --> 01:04:13,109
Phyllis is right. You should
think it over. It's been a rough 15 rounds.

1079
01:04:13,187 --> 01:04:15,985
No, there's nothing to think about.
Tell them no.

1080
01:04:19,660 --> 01:04:23,391
Bob, let's take a bird's
eye view for a moment, okay?

1081
01:04:23,898 --> 01:04:28,597
First off, if you're really thinking
of turning this down and going to court,

1082
01:04:28,669 --> 01:04:31,137
that's a very
expensive proposition.

1083
01:04:31,205 --> 01:04:33,696
It's not a good...
It's not a good play.

1084
01:04:33,774 --> 01:04:36,208
I'm not talking about
play, Mr. Lawson.

1085
01:04:36,877 --> 01:04:39,277
Let me just tell you something
for future reference, Bob.

1086
01:04:39,346 --> 01:04:42,406
I don't appreciate the
way you're talking to me.

1087
01:04:43,484 --> 01:04:45,975
You don't have the most
charming personality.

1088
01:04:46,053 --> 01:04:49,284
And at least four times a
week, I get a call from you

1089
01:04:49,356 --> 01:04:50,687
telling me what
the law is.

1090
01:04:50,758 --> 01:04:53,591
You're not a lawyer,
Dr. Kearns.

1091
01:04:53,661 --> 01:05:00,066
Now, from a real lawyer, from a 45-year
member of the bar, I can tell you,

1092
01:05:00,701 --> 01:05:04,262
this firm has spent more time on
your case than you can comprehend.

1093
01:05:04,338 --> 01:05:07,034
Maybe. But you're getting
money for this case.

1094
01:05:07,108 --> 01:05:08,336
Only if we settle.

1095
01:05:08,409 --> 01:05:10,934
Bob, think it over.
It's essential.

1096
01:05:11,011 --> 01:05:15,380
Three, maybe $400,000, it's
enough to change your whole life.

1097
01:05:15,449 --> 01:05:16,507
I'm sure it would.

1098
01:05:16,584 --> 01:05:17,881
It certainly seems
like a lot.

1099
01:05:17,952 --> 01:05:18,941
It doesn't matter.

1100
01:05:19,019 --> 01:05:21,886
Look, I'm sure you men think
this is a bunch of hogwash,

1101
01:05:21,956 --> 01:05:24,356
but this is about
more than money.

1102
01:05:24,925 --> 01:05:27,052
I always thought I was put here
on this earth for a purpose.

1103
01:05:27,128 --> 01:05:30,894
I thought it was to be an engineer.
Or maybe an inventor.

1104
01:05:30,965 --> 01:05:33,456
But that's not it.
And now I know what it is.

1105
01:05:33,534 --> 01:05:35,968
God put you here to sue
the Ford Motor Company?

1106
01:05:36,036 --> 01:05:39,597
Look, I brought these here, thinking
that you had different ideas.

1107
01:05:39,673 --> 01:05:42,642
Edwin Armstrong
invented the FM radio.

1108
01:05:42,710 --> 01:05:44,337
Somehow R.C.A. ended
up with the patent.

1109
01:05:44,411 --> 01:05:48,108
He jumped out a 13-story window.
This was a good man!

1110
01:05:48,182 --> 01:05:51,948
He was an inventor.
And, look, I have letters from people.

1111
01:05:52,019 --> 01:05:54,419
People who've had their
ideas taken from them.

1112
01:05:54,488 --> 01:05:57,548
They've heard about us. They're in
their backyards and their garages,

1113
01:05:57,625 --> 01:06:00,025
and they're counting on me.
Please, just look at this.

1114
01:06:00,094 --> 01:06:02,358
Thank you very much. I really don't
need to look at these right now.

1115
01:06:02,429 --> 01:06:04,795
Let's just get to
the point. Okay?

1116
01:06:04,865 --> 01:06:07,959
This settlement offer
is very, very generous.

1117
01:06:08,035 --> 01:06:10,162
And if we did get
this before a jury,

1118
01:06:10,237 --> 01:06:11,864
if we prevailed,

1119
01:06:11,939 --> 01:06:15,705
if the jury gave you the
recognition you so obviously crave...

1120
01:06:15,776 --> 01:06:16,834
That's insulting.

1121
01:06:16,911 --> 01:06:19,379
...it is doubtful that
you would do any better

1122
01:06:19,446 --> 01:06:21,380
than you would right now
with this settlement.

1123
01:06:21,448 --> 01:06:24,781
And whatever happened to this little
thing called justice you talked about?

1124
01:06:24,852 --> 01:06:28,447
This is justice, Bob. This is how
justice is dispensed in this country.

1125
01:06:28,522 --> 01:06:29,682
With checkbooks.

1126
01:06:29,757 --> 01:06:32,988
There are no brass bands, you know.
There are no ticker tape parades.

1127
01:06:33,060 --> 01:06:35,153
The mayor doesn't give
you the key to the city

1128
01:06:35,229 --> 01:06:37,129
and call you a hero.
You get a check.

1129
01:06:37,198 --> 01:06:41,134
And that check makes the lives of
you and your family a little easier.

1130
01:06:41,202 --> 01:06:43,898
A little more pleasant.
It's that simple.

1131
01:06:43,971 --> 01:06:47,304
Well, I'll make it simple, too.
Forget the check.

1132
01:06:47,942 --> 01:06:51,309
Get an admission that they stole it
and give me the right to manufacture

1133
01:06:51,378 --> 01:06:54,541
my wipers and
this'll all be over.

1134
01:06:54,882 --> 01:06:59,945
Bob, since I bought this wasted champagne,
just indulge me for a moment, okay?

1135
01:07:00,020 --> 01:07:03,717
Just think about
this scenario.

1136
01:07:03,791 --> 01:07:07,056
Your lawsuit is over.
But you know what?

1137
01:07:07,127 --> 01:07:09,527
You're no longer
a young man. Why?

1138
01:07:09,597 --> 01:07:12,498
Because you're fighting a
corporation that, that does not

1139
01:07:12,566 --> 01:07:15,558
know the meaning
of years. Or money.

1140
01:07:16,604 --> 01:07:20,768
They'll bury you with motions,
injunctions, countersuits.

1141
01:07:20,841 --> 01:07:25,073
They'll drown you in so many irrelevant
documents that you'll wake up,

1142
01:07:25,145 --> 01:07:27,739
with cold sweats.

1143
01:07:27,815 --> 01:07:30,409
And five years from now,
you won't be any closer

1144
01:07:30,484 --> 01:07:33,317
to seeing the inside of a
courtroom than you are right now.

1145
01:07:33,387 --> 01:07:35,514
Your hair will turn gray.

1146
01:07:35,589 --> 01:07:38,149
Life will pass you by.
And for what?

1147
01:07:39,159 --> 01:07:42,560
Go home and talk about this with
your lovely wife. Sleep on it.

1148
01:07:43,731 --> 01:07:47,963
And then make your decision. And if you
make the decision that I hope you will,

1149
01:07:48,369 --> 01:07:50,462
this'll all be over
in a few days.

1150
01:07:54,241 --> 01:07:56,175
I'll show you what we got here
in the stacks on patent law,

1151
01:07:56,243 --> 01:07:59,269
but there's a load more over
at the university library.

1152
01:07:59,713 --> 01:08:01,476
And here you go.

1153
01:08:02,383 --> 01:08:05,443
Oh, so it's all this?

1154
01:08:06,020 --> 01:08:07,783
Nope, and those shelves, too.

1155
01:08:07,855 --> 01:08:12,690
And that one there.
And half of that one, I think.

1156
01:08:14,461 --> 01:08:15,723
Thanks, Louis.

1157
01:08:16,196 --> 01:08:17,493
You're welcome.

1158
01:08:26,206 --> 01:08:28,003
I'm sorry it's so late.

1159
01:08:28,075 --> 01:08:30,566
Uh-huh. I couldn't sleep.

1160
01:08:31,946 --> 01:08:34,915
Well, no turning into me.

1161
01:08:39,119 --> 01:08:40,586
No turning into me.

1162
01:08:41,522 --> 01:08:43,513
Honey, I think we
should take the deal.

1163
01:08:45,993 --> 01:08:48,894
Well, I know you do.
But I don't.

1164
01:08:50,230 --> 01:08:52,198
Robert, it's gone on
long enough now.

1165
01:08:52,266 --> 01:08:53,631
We could really use the money.

1166
01:08:53,701 --> 01:08:55,191
Since when has this
been about money?

1167
01:08:55,269 --> 01:08:57,703
It's not just about the money.
It's about our family.

1168
01:08:57,771 --> 01:08:59,966
Well, why do you
think I'm doing this?

1169
01:09:00,040 --> 01:09:02,600
How am I supposed to teach my
kids about doing the right thing

1170
01:09:02,676 --> 01:09:04,200
if I let these guys
get away with this?

1171
01:09:04,278 --> 01:09:06,246
I'm not sure that's exactly
what we're teaching them.

1172
01:09:06,313 --> 01:09:08,281
They like this.
The kids like being involved in it.

1173
01:09:08,349 --> 01:09:12,149
No, they just don't want to let you down.
I don't want to let you down.

1174
01:09:17,224 --> 01:09:18,486
We're fine.

1175
01:09:22,062 --> 01:09:25,623
It's like he said.
They have all the time. We don't.

1176
01:09:26,633 --> 01:09:29,158
We're gonna be fine.

1177
01:09:51,759 --> 01:09:54,091
Is that the Journal?
- Yeah, 1949.

1178
01:09:54,161 --> 01:09:56,322
<i>Gerald Reed vs.</i>
<i>Lansing Tech.</i>

1179
01:09:56,930 --> 01:09:58,090
Seems relevant, huh?

1180
01:09:58,165 --> 01:09:59,655
Seems like it to me.

1181
01:10:00,334 --> 01:10:03,394
Dr. Kearns,
I'm really glad you're doing this.

1182
01:10:03,604 --> 01:10:07,597
<i>The truth is, if you don't fight,
the rest of us will never stand a chance.</i>

1183
01:10:17,451 --> 01:10:18,475
Hey.
- Hey.

1184
01:10:23,457 --> 01:10:25,118
How you doing?

1185
01:10:25,492 --> 01:10:27,289
Good. Mr. Lawson called.

1186
01:10:28,362 --> 01:10:31,354
Okay. Where are the kids?

1187
01:10:31,432 --> 01:10:32,956
I took them to Deb's.

1188
01:10:38,072 --> 01:10:40,666
Okay. I'm gonna grab a...

1189
01:10:46,380 --> 01:10:47,369
Phyllis...

1190
01:10:47,448 --> 01:10:48,745
I wrote you a letter.

1191
01:10:51,452 --> 01:10:54,046
And I threw it away, 'cause
I don't know what to say.

1192
01:10:54,888 --> 01:10:57,413
It's just become
so destructive.

1193
01:10:57,491 --> 01:11:00,949
Okay, listen.
I heard everything you said last week,

1194
01:11:01,028 --> 01:11:03,394
and I agree with it.
I'm trying to change...

1195
01:11:03,464 --> 01:11:06,228
No, I know.
I know you want to change.

1196
01:11:06,300 --> 01:11:08,427
I don't think you know how.

1197
01:11:08,535 --> 01:11:09,934
You can't.
- This is just how it has to be.

1198
01:11:10,003 --> 01:11:10,992
Phyllis...

1199
01:11:11,071 --> 01:11:12,231
I'm leaving.
- No.

1200
01:11:12,306 --> 01:11:15,901
Because I think this is the right thing.
Please understand.

1201
01:11:16,176 --> 01:11:19,339
This has overwhelmed us.
- Goddamn it, I need you right now!

1202
01:11:19,446 --> 01:11:22,210
You've stopped supporting
me ever since I got home!

1203
01:11:22,282 --> 01:11:25,251
You don't believe in this case anymore.
It's not, this isn't fair.

1204
01:11:25,319 --> 01:11:27,480
It's not fair!
- It's not fair to me.

1205
01:11:27,588 --> 01:11:31,285
There are seven other people in this
house, and you just don't get it.

1206
01:11:31,358 --> 01:11:34,486
We're close. We're so close.
They're calling us right now!

1207
01:11:34,561 --> 01:11:37,689
Honey. No.
- Phyllis, no, Phyllis.

1208
01:11:37,831 --> 01:11:40,322
Come here.
We're okay.

1209
01:11:42,936 --> 01:11:44,836
I can't do it without you.

1210
01:11:44,905 --> 01:11:46,532
You're gonna be fine.

1211
01:11:47,441 --> 01:11:48,669
I can fix it.

1212
01:11:50,010 --> 01:11:55,607
Okay. You fix it.
And then we'll see, okay?

1213
01:11:57,184 --> 01:11:59,175
For now, this is best.

1214
01:11:59,586 --> 01:12:00,985
You still love me?

1215
01:12:03,490 --> 01:12:04,855
I love you.

1216
01:12:14,134 --> 01:12:15,226
What did Lawson say?

1217
01:12:15,302 --> 01:12:19,671
He officially
resigned the case.

1218
01:13:23,370 --> 01:13:25,395
Yeah, so, I'm going
back to my room real quick,

1219
01:13:25,472 --> 01:13:26,530
and then I'll meet
you at the library.

1220
01:13:26,607 --> 01:13:27,904
Dennis?

1221
01:13:29,676 --> 01:13:30,734
Dad.

1222
01:13:32,512 --> 01:13:34,173
I'll catch up with you guys.

1223
01:13:34,248 --> 01:13:35,977
Yeah, see you later.

1224
01:13:38,352 --> 01:13:40,980
Hey. What's going on?

1225
01:13:41,054 --> 01:13:42,851
Can we get
a cup of coffee?

1226
01:13:44,258 --> 01:13:45,850
Sure. Yeah.

1227
01:13:49,096 --> 01:13:50,085
It's a long article, Dad.

1228
01:13:50,163 --> 01:13:52,188
Just keep reading.

1229
01:13:52,266 --> 01:13:53,563
Where?
- Well, down here.

1230
01:13:53,634 --> 01:13:54,965
Look. Okay?

1231
01:13:56,136 --> 01:13:57,660
"Among other things,
the new courts are

1232
01:13:57,738 --> 01:13:59,729
"designed to free up
the logjam of patent cases

1233
01:13:59,806 --> 01:14:01,433
"that have been clogging
the federal courts."

1234
01:14:01,508 --> 01:14:04,739
Do you know what that means?
We can actually get to court.

1235
01:14:05,545 --> 01:14:09,242
They've been waiting me out.
They're waiting for my patents to expire.

1236
01:14:09,316 --> 01:14:12,547
And if we can get them to court
soon, they lose a very big advantage.

1237
01:14:12,619 --> 01:14:16,316
How soon?
- Months. Months, not years.

1238
01:14:18,692 --> 01:14:20,353
That's great, Dad.

1239
01:14:21,995 --> 01:14:24,793
Well, I'm not ready yet.

1240
01:14:24,865 --> 01:14:27,197
And I can't do this by myself.

1241
01:14:29,336 --> 01:14:30,735
Hey.

1242
01:14:30,804 --> 01:14:33,034
We used to talk about the Kearns
Corporation. You remember that?

1243
01:14:33,106 --> 01:14:34,437
That was a joke, Dad.

1244
01:14:34,508 --> 01:14:37,773
Not to me.
That was never a joke.

1245
01:14:37,844 --> 01:14:40,335
We weren't a corporation.
We were a family.

1246
01:14:40,814 --> 01:14:42,839
We haven't even been that.

1247
01:14:43,317 --> 01:14:49,256
I need help, Dennis. I submitted
a request to Ford for one document.

1248
01:14:50,424 --> 01:14:55,225
They sent me back 357 pages. I had to read
through every one to find the relevant page.

1249
01:14:56,797 --> 01:15:01,393
That is all you care about.
That's all you ever cared about, Dad.

1250
01:15:02,736 --> 01:15:05,637
Thanks for the coffee.
I gotta get to class.

1251
01:15:07,507 --> 01:15:09,634
Okay. I'm fine.

1252
01:15:09,776 --> 01:15:12,870
Go ahead. Go to your class.
I don't need the help.

1253
01:15:40,240 --> 01:15:41,764
Can I help you?

1254
01:15:42,342 --> 01:15:43,570
I hope so.

1255
01:15:44,945 --> 01:15:48,847
Bob Kearns?
My name is Charlie Defao.

1256
01:15:49,850 --> 01:15:51,340
What do you want?

1257
01:15:51,485 --> 01:15:56,252
A conversation. We tried calling, but
you don't answer your phone much, do you?

1258
01:15:57,457 --> 01:15:58,617
Who are you?

1259
01:15:58,692 --> 01:16:01,126
I'm here at the request
of the Ford Motor Company.

1260
01:16:01,194 --> 01:16:03,856
You think we could go inside
and discuss a few things?

1261
01:16:03,930 --> 01:16:06,057
Discuss what?

1262
01:16:06,133 --> 01:16:08,363
How about putting
all this behind you?

1263
01:16:09,102 --> 01:16:10,660
So you can move
on with your life.

1264
01:16:10,737 --> 01:16:14,503
And so, frankly, Ford can stop
devoting so much time to your concerns.

1265
01:16:15,609 --> 01:16:17,372
Well, they can if they want.

1266
01:16:17,444 --> 01:16:18,570
They want.

1267
01:16:18,645 --> 01:16:21,944
And to prove it, they've authorized me
to come here and offer you a lot of money.

1268
01:16:22,015 --> 01:16:24,313
On top of your legal expenses.

1269
01:16:26,853 --> 01:16:27,842
I accept.

1270
01:16:29,189 --> 01:16:30,884
Excellent.

1271
01:16:30,957 --> 01:16:32,356
On one condition.

1272
01:16:33,627 --> 01:16:37,825
As long as Ford takes out an ad in
the <i>Detroit Free Press,</i>

1273
01:16:37,898 --> 01:16:39,559
saying that they stole
Robert Kearns' invention,

1274
01:16:39,633 --> 01:16:42,932
and have done everything they
can to deny me my day in court.

1275
01:16:44,504 --> 01:16:46,404
The only problem with that

1276
01:16:48,241 --> 01:16:50,334
is that it'd
be a lie. Huh?

1277
01:16:51,511 --> 01:16:53,706
To say they stole your
invention would be an insult.

1278
01:16:53,780 --> 01:16:57,147
To every engineer, stockholder, every
single man and woman at the company.

1279
01:16:57,217 --> 01:17:01,017
Bob, Ford is genuinely sorry
if you've ever felt mistreated.

1280
01:17:02,055 --> 01:17:04,853
And to resolve the situation, they're
willing to take the first step.

1281
01:17:04,925 --> 01:17:06,790
A big step.
Frankly, an amazing step.

1282
01:17:07,894 --> 01:17:09,418
A million dollar step.

1283
01:17:11,798 --> 01:17:14,892
I have work to do and
you're keeping me from it.

1284
01:17:15,902 --> 01:17:18,530
I hate to use these words,
but in this case,

1285
01:17:18,605 --> 01:17:21,165
this actually is a take
it or leave it offer.

1286
01:17:24,511 --> 01:17:27,241
Bob, you don't want
this in court, okay?

1287
01:17:29,616 --> 01:17:32,551
Going to the law library's not
gonna make you a lawyer, Bob.

1288
01:17:32,619 --> 01:17:36,487
Look, I'm gonna leave you my card,
okay? I've put my home number on it.

1289
01:17:36,723 --> 01:17:39,692
So I want you to call
me anytime. Day or night.

1290
01:17:40,961 --> 01:17:42,258
Doesn't matter.

1291
01:17:43,163 --> 01:17:46,132
Just call me. I'll be waiting
for your call, Bob, okay?

1292
01:17:47,100 --> 01:17:49,432
Just not for long.

1293
01:17:51,571 --> 01:17:52,560
Asshole.

1294
01:17:56,710 --> 01:17:57,699
Asshole.

1295
01:17:59,145 --> 01:18:01,545
There he is. Hey, Dad!

1296
01:18:01,648 --> 01:18:03,513
Hi, honey.

1297
01:18:04,851 --> 01:18:06,011
Hey, Dennis.

1298
01:18:06,620 --> 01:18:08,747
Hey, Dad.

1299
01:18:08,822 --> 01:18:10,312
You want to come in?

1300
01:18:11,124 --> 01:18:13,752
No, I'll see you, okay?

1301
01:18:14,227 --> 01:18:17,355
Okay. How are you?

1302
01:18:17,597 --> 01:18:19,087
I'm good.
- Yeah?

1303
01:18:19,199 --> 01:18:20,689
How you doing?

1304
01:18:21,234 --> 01:18:22,997
Dennis, hold up!

1305
01:18:27,173 --> 01:18:28,538
Hey.
- Hey.

1306
01:18:30,143 --> 01:18:31,974
Thanks for bringing
Kathy over.

1307
01:18:32,045 --> 01:18:33,535
You're welcome.

1308
01:18:33,914 --> 01:18:37,350
Yeah. Thanks for bringing
her over the last time, too.

1309
01:18:37,417 --> 01:18:38,679
You know?

1310
01:18:41,121 --> 01:18:43,715
I know you've carried a pretty
big load for the family, Dennis.

1311
01:18:43,790 --> 01:18:46,281
It's okay, Dad.

1312
01:18:46,860 --> 01:18:49,658
I just want you to know
you're pretty good at it.

1313
01:18:50,597 --> 01:18:53,088
You're better than
most guys I know.

1314
01:18:53,266 --> 01:18:55,166
Thank you.

1315
01:18:58,872 --> 01:19:00,100
I'll see you.

1316
01:19:01,141 --> 01:19:02,130
See you.

1317
01:19:04,744 --> 01:19:06,541
Everything all right?

1318
01:19:06,913 --> 01:19:09,381
What do you want to do?

1319
01:19:09,449 --> 01:19:11,849
Don't you have a lot of work?
I just figured I'd help out.

1320
01:19:11,918 --> 01:19:14,113
Hey, you work too much.

1321
01:19:15,255 --> 01:19:18,019
Too much typing.
Let's, go have some fun.

1322
01:19:19,192 --> 01:19:22,992
I hear there's a... There's a
car show at the Historical Museum.

1323
01:19:23,063 --> 01:19:24,428
We could...

1324
01:19:24,497 --> 01:19:26,522
Wow! That is something
different.

1325
01:19:26,633 --> 01:19:27,759
Oh, that's very funny.

1326
01:20:21,721 --> 01:20:22,847
Hey, Dad.

1327
01:20:22,922 --> 01:20:23,911
Oh!

1328
01:20:25,925 --> 01:20:27,859
You scared the hell out of me.

1329
01:20:28,461 --> 01:20:29,826
Sorry.

1330
01:20:30,563 --> 01:20:31,723
Yeah.

1331
01:20:35,969 --> 01:20:40,030
I got some coffees for us.
Looks like a long night.

1332
01:20:44,044 --> 01:20:47,946
Thank you.
Uh, yeah, son.

1333
01:20:50,650 --> 01:20:51,810
Right. Okay.

1334
01:20:52,052 --> 01:20:56,045
Mr. Finley, Dr. Kearns,
please step up into the well.

1335
01:20:57,290 --> 01:21:00,344
Civil action, <i>Robert Kearns
vs. the Ford Motor Company,</i>

1336
01:21:00,345 --> 01:21:01,556
will begin on August 14th.

1337
01:21:01,628 --> 01:21:05,587
United States District Court for
the Eastern District of Michigan.

1338
01:21:05,665 --> 01:21:09,658
So, Dr. Kearns, I'm not
sure why, since you seem like

1339
01:21:09,736 --> 01:21:13,763
a reasonable man, but I understand
you'll be representing yourself.

1340
01:21:14,140 --> 01:21:18,634
Yes, sir.
My son Dennis will be helping me out.

1341
01:21:19,212 --> 01:21:24,115
Okay, then if you're up for it, let's make
it a good clean fight, shall we, gentlemen?

1342
01:21:24,784 --> 01:21:26,718
Of course we will, Your Honor.

1343
01:21:27,754 --> 01:21:29,278
I don't understand.

1344
01:21:29,355 --> 01:21:31,653
It's just an expression,
Dr. Kearns.

1345
01:21:32,692 --> 01:21:35,320
August 14th.
We'll see you then.

1346
01:21:35,495 --> 01:21:37,326
Thank you very much,
Your Honor.

1347
01:21:37,397 --> 01:21:39,331
Thank you very much,
Your Honor.

1348
01:21:43,169 --> 01:21:44,500
How's Mom?

1349
01:21:45,138 --> 01:21:46,298
She's fine.

1350
01:21:48,341 --> 01:21:49,774
You want the dates on these?

1351
01:21:52,045 --> 01:21:53,034
Yeah.

1352
01:21:53,113 --> 01:21:54,307
Quit your bitching.
You're only carrying one.

1353
01:21:54,380 --> 01:21:55,369
Tough.

1354
01:21:55,448 --> 01:21:57,313
Hey, put those by the wall.
- There you go.

1355
01:21:57,383 --> 01:21:59,146
Is it Chrysler?
- Hell if I know.

1356
01:21:59,219 --> 01:22:02,848
Watch your language.
She'll be coming to the trial, right?

1357
01:22:03,223 --> 01:22:05,987
Look, Dad, I told you not to
get your hopes up about Mom.

1358
01:22:06,059 --> 01:22:09,426
Well, what does that mean?

1359
01:22:09,863 --> 01:22:11,694
You know what that means.

1360
01:22:12,632 --> 01:22:15,260
No, I really don't.

1361
01:22:15,902 --> 01:22:18,462
She's busy.
She's doing a lot of substituting.

1362
01:22:24,644 --> 01:22:26,509
Is she seeing someone?

1363
01:22:28,248 --> 01:22:30,648
It's been four years, Dad.

1364
01:22:30,717 --> 01:22:32,947
Well, that's not
an answer, Kath.

1365
01:22:36,022 --> 01:22:41,619
Well, anyway, it's okay.
Just let her know. It'd be nice.

1366
01:22:41,728 --> 01:22:42,888
Mmm.

1367
01:22:52,739 --> 01:22:54,036
What a piece of crap.

1368
01:22:54,107 --> 01:22:55,540
It's perfect.

1369
01:23:07,587 --> 01:23:12,490
Hi, Phyllis. Um, I know it's
late. The kids are asleep,

1370
01:23:14,093 --> 01:23:17,893
and I think I've been putting off
this call hoping you would be, too.

1371
01:23:18,331 --> 01:23:23,564
I just wanted you to know
that the trial starts tomorrow.

1372
01:23:27,740 --> 01:23:29,901
Okay. Good-bye.

1373
01:23:45,525 --> 01:23:46,617
Hey, Dad!

1374
01:23:46,693 --> 01:23:48,661
Hey, Dad wait up!

1375
01:23:48,728 --> 01:23:50,161
Hey. How are you?

1376
01:23:50,230 --> 01:23:51,561
Good. How are you?
- Hello, Patrick.

1377
01:23:51,631 --> 01:23:53,724
Hey.
- I'm doing pretty good.

1378
01:23:56,502 --> 01:23:58,663
You get some rest?
- Oh, a little bit.

1379
01:23:58,838 --> 01:24:03,537
Most of the testimony you'll be hearing at
this trial will be highly technical in nature.

1380
01:24:03,610 --> 01:24:07,637
Although you may have noticed a
less technical piece of evidence

1381
01:24:07,747 --> 01:24:10,272
in the form of half
of an automobile.

1382
01:24:11,317 --> 01:24:14,548
The plaintiff in this case
is Dr. Robert Kearns.

1383
01:24:14,621 --> 01:24:19,524
Dr. Kearns charges that the Ford Motor Company
infringed five patents that he holds.

1384
01:24:19,626 --> 01:24:22,891
If you decide in Dr. Kearns'
favor, you will also decide

1385
01:24:22,996 --> 01:24:26,056
what damages, if any,
are due to Dr. Kearns.

1386
01:24:26,766 --> 01:24:30,998
Dr. Kearns has voluntarily chosen
to represent himself at this trial.

1387
01:24:31,104 --> 01:24:35,541
You are not to draw any inferences
either for or against Dr. Kearns,

1388
01:24:35,808 --> 01:24:38,652
simply because he
is representing himself.

1389
01:24:38,653 --> 01:24:39,710
Yes, Dr. Kearns?

1390
01:24:41,014 --> 01:24:45,713
I just wanted to thank you for
allowing me to represent myself

1391
01:24:45,785 --> 01:24:47,946
and introduce my son,
Dennis Kearns.

1392
01:24:51,391 --> 01:24:53,484
Is that all, Dr. Kearns?

1393
01:24:53,993 --> 01:24:57,588
I appreciate the jury giving their
time to the community like this.

1394
01:24:58,064 --> 01:25:00,965
The jury is the
conscience of the community.

1395
01:25:04,270 --> 01:25:05,897
Are you finished?

1396
01:25:06,205 --> 01:25:09,572
You might be more comfortable
seated, don't you think?

1397
01:25:10,643 --> 01:25:14,579
Please keep in mind you're not to discuss
what you hear at this trial with anyone else.

1398
01:25:14,681 --> 01:25:17,115
Not amongst yourselves, not in the
jury room, not in the hallway...

1399
